<P>
ALMOST ALL OF THE WESTERN FINALISTS AGREE WITH CHOICE OF MAGIC AS MVP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SAM McMANIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PORTLAND, Ore. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nearly every player on the Phoenix Suns and the Portland Trail Blazers said 
Tuesday that the Lakers' Magic Johnson deserved his second consecutive NBA 
most-valuable-player honor, although most diplomatically added that any of six 
players could have been selected. 
</P>
<P>
"The man deserves it," Trail Blazer forward Buck Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
"Magic is the best player that's come down the pike in a long time. He is 
phenomenal, but he makes people like A.C. Green, Mychal Thompson and Vlade 
Divac better players." 
</P>
<P>
The lone dissenting vote was cast by Portland guard Clyde Drexler. Although 
Drexler did not begrudge Johnson the honor, he said he would have voted for 
fellow Houstonian Akeem Olajuwon. 
</P>
<P>
"Any time you pick Magic Johnson for MVP, you can't go wrong," Drexler said. 
"But maybe I'm a little biased. I would've taken Akeem. It's hard to overlook 
his statistics. He was up there in almost every category." SAM McMANIS 
</P>
</TEXT>
