<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: IRVINE; 
</P>
<P>
OVERPASS EXPANSION FOE IS THREATENED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANICA KIRKA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A leader in the fight to block expansion of the Yale Avenue pedestrian 
overpasses said Tuesday that he had received a death threat. 
</P>
<P>
David Flint, treasurer of a group that wants the bridges to remain restricted 
to pedestrians, bicyclists and emergency vehicles, played the tape of the phone 
call at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
The caller said, "How dare you use our money for political causes," and said 
Flint's family and home were in jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
"What the hell is happening behind the nice, glossy, planned community?" Flint 
asked. "There are wackos out there." 
</P>
<P>
The threat also prompted outrage from Yale Action, the group advocating 
expansion of the overpasses. 
</P>
<P>
"It's not appropriate at all. It's not right," said Gary Vanderpol, the 
treasurer of Yale Action. "That's not the kind of campaign we're running." 
</P>
<P>
Flint said the threat followed the distribution of a flyer challenging a 
decision by the Deerfield Homeowners Assn. to donate $2,500 to Flint's group, 
the Friends of Caution for Neighborhood Preservation. The flyer, which lists 
Flint's phone number and address, claims that the homeowners' association will 
lose its tax-exempt status if it makes the contribution. The flyer was 
distributed by two former officials in the Deerfield Homeowners Assn. 
</P>
<P>
But the association doesn't have tax-exempt status now, Flint said. Flint, vice 
president of the association, said it has budgeted $6,000 of its $350,000 
annual budget for taxes this year. 
</P>
<P>
One of the authors of the flyer said he had assumed that the association had 
tax-exempt status. 
</P>
<P>
On June 5, voters will decide whether the bridges on Yale Avenue over the 
Atchison Topeka &amp; Santa Fe railroad tracks and over the San Diego Freeway 
should be expanded to accommodate two-lane vehicular traffic. DANICA KIRKA 
</P>
</TEXT>
