<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIZ SMITH: 'LOLITA' COMING BACK -- WITHOUT THE '62 NO-NOS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Liz Smith 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THE RETURN of "Lolita"? Yes. Agent Irving Lazar sold Vladimir Nabokov's classic 
novel -- about a mature man obsessed by a 14-year-old nymphet -- about 25 years 
ago. It was then made into a wonderful 1962 movie, directed by the great 
Stanley Kubrick via MGM/7 Arts/Allied Artists. 
</P>
<P>
Now the film rights have returned to Nabokov's estate representative, Nikki 
Smith, and Smith and Lazar have sold "Lolita" all over again -- to Carolco 
Pictures International, a major independent. 
</P>
<P>
Their asking price this time was $1 million, and "Fatal Attraction" director 
Adrian Lyne is to be at the movie's helm. 
</P>
<P>
You do remember the original, a movie somewhat hampered by the strictures, 
mores and no-nos of the time. Noel Coward and Laurence Olivier were each sought 
for the leading role of the lecherous Humbert Humbert, who marries Lolita's 
mother to be near his heart's desire. James Mason ended up playing the role, 
with Sue Lyon as the nubile adolescent, Shelley Winters as her mother, and 
Peter Sellers as the driven observer, Quilty. 
</P>
<P>
So, you can begin casting in your head for the new Carolco version that will 
allow unhampered license in this day and age to Nabokov's exquisite, delicious 
and literary story. (This freedom does not necessarily mean the film will be 
improved upon in Version 2. After all, Nabokov wrote his own screenplay and was 
Oscar-nominated for the effort.) 
</P>
<P>
THE NEW YORK POPS has become a highly visible "hit" after seven uphill years of 
striving annually at Carnegie Hall in a night sponsored by The New York Daily 
News. It seems Skitch Henderson and his musicians have "arrived" at last, 
mysteriously, as in all "overnight" successes. Even the dinner after was a hit 
in the Plaza Ballroom. 
</P>
<P>
We ended with a vulnerable Liza Minnelli, paying tribute to New York and to 
Sammy Davis Jr. in a rousing and sentimental finale. 
</P>
<P>
IN SPITE of the poor reviews, producer David Brown announces that "The Cemetery 
Club," Ivan Menchell's comedy at the Brooks Atkinson Theater in New York, has 
been acquired by Disney for Touchstone Pictures. Let's hope they also take the 
award-winning actors -- Eileen Heckart, Elizabeth Franz and Doris Belack. I 
wouldn't listen to the critics on this one; audiences seem crazy about this 
play. Brown has become the hottest new boy on the block. He also has "Tru" and 
"A Few Good Men" on Broadway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Vladimir Nabokov in 1976. JILL KREMENTZ 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
